Putin is the culprit
Medical experts from Moscow, Germany, France, and Sweden are in agreement: Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is Russia's largest opponent of President Putin and also the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Luckily, since Navalny was able to survive, the relationship between Russia and Germany did not deteriorate.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel announced that Navalny is a "victim persecuted for freedom of speech."
In her eyes, this incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond.
She emphasizes that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel calls on the Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the results of the investigation prove that the Russian government was behind the incident, the European Commission will impose new sanctions.
Regardless, according to the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, poisoning is a prohibited act.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok to target its political enemies.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied any involvement in both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted that "there is no evidence to accuse the Russian government."
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service Director Sergei Naryshkin even said this is the action of Western intelligence agencies, trying to discredit the Russian government.
Naryshkin's statement is obviously an attempt to deflect, but he also said one fact: the Navalny case is a liability for Russia.
Poisoning a prominent political opponent just before the election is unacceptable, especially when the poison is a Soviet-era developed agent.
This timing is particularly noteworthy, especially as Belarusian citizens are protesting against the August election in neighboring Belarus.
The Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny case is also particularly puzzling.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If it was indeed the Russian government, as Germany claims, then this murder was also a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of the international stage (the main antagonist in the movie "Star Wars"), interfering in US elections, inciting French street protests, pushing for Brexit, and propping up Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he is cunning, far-sighted, and deceitful.
So why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why did Navalny manage to flee to Germany and was quickly diagnosed with being poisoned?
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, and the Nord Stream 2 pipeline project to Germany is facing cancellation.
This murder is clearly a failure.
In fact, it has only sparked more public opposition to the evil deeds of the Russian authorities.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, the claim that it was the Western intelligence agencies is even more exaggerated.
If such an accusation were true, scientists in Germany and Sweden would not have confirmed the fact of the nerve agent Novichok.
More likely, it comes from a conspiracy orchestrated by Putin's inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needs Navalny to keep quiet before the election, or perhaps his anti-corruption investigation has caused trouble.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services, including military-grade nerve agents, on the black market.
Putin's political thugs may be loyal but are foolish, thinking that poisoning Navalny was a good idea, with only a few involved knowing the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts share similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza was the coordinator of the Human Rights Council of Russia.
The poisoning of Peter Verzilov, the publisher of independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on human rights abuses by Russia's judiciary.
Going even further back, there was the poisoning of former KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko in 2006. Litvinenko frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
Like the Navalny case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, liberal newspaper columnist Anna Politkovskaya was poisoned on a flight from Moscow to Beslan, although she managed to survive, she was later shot dead in the elevator of her apartment two years later.
As Putin said, her death caused massive damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin.
Whether Putin was directly involved or not, his system allowed such crimes to happen. This system is both ineffective and useless, and it's a farce involving some shameless actors.
Navalny's death was the desired result for the Kremlin, and making Putin happy was the ultimate goal for the yes-men.
In Putin's circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning fails, they won't face punishment.
Because they did it for the president's benefit.
Those who might be looking for evidence of the poisoning might be disappointed.
Regardless, the Kremlin is the mastermind.
Western countries must take a clear stance, even if their own economy is affected, and impose sanctions on Russia.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All responsibility for what happens in Russia falls on him alone.
